<subSubSection pageId="761" pageNumber="762" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="761" pageNumber="762">
<taxonomicName LSID="F9566A88-6ADD-66DB-0425-C66DDBC108D1" authority="(Bates, 1882)" baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1882" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Agonum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Agonum cyanopis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="761" pageNumber="762" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanopis">Agonum cyanopis (Bates, 1882)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="761" pageNumber="762" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="761" pageNumber="762">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1882" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Anchomenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="761" pageNumber="762" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanopis">Anchomenus cyanopis</taxonomicName>
Bates, 1882a: 94. Type locality: &quot;Guanajuato, Mexico&quot; (original citation for the lectotype). Lectotype (â™‚), designated by Liebherr (1982: 153), in BMNH. Note. The specific name probably derives from the Latin adjective 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">cyaneus</emphasis>
, - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">a</emphasis>
, - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">um</emphasis>
(dark blue) and the Latin noun 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">ops</emphasis>
, - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">opis</emphasis>
(riches, wealth) and refers to the dark blue coloration of the adult. The ending of the name remains unchanged whether the name is combined with a masculine generic name such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonelli" authorityYear="1810" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Anchomenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="761" pageNumber="762" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">Anchomenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or a neutral generic name such as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonelli" authorityYear="1810" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Agonum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="761" pageNumber="762" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">Agonum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The spelling 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bates" baseAuthorityYear="1882" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Agonum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="761" pageNumber="762" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cyanope">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="761" pageNumber="762">Agonum cyanope</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, used by modern authors since the 1980s, is incorrect.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="761" pageNumber="762" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="761" pageNumber="762">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="761" pageNumber="762">This species is found from eastern Arizona and western New Mexico south through the Sierra Madre Occidental to the Mexican states of Guerrero, Puebla, and Vera Cruz [see Liebherr 1986: Fig. 37].</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
